            </DerivedFrom>
        </Component>

        <Component>
            <ID>CMP--18</ID>
            <Name>Periodic Control Loop Scheduler</Name>
            <Purpose>
                Provides periodic control loop with period T and ensures required execution sequence of sensor acquisition, mapping, mission control, planning, and motor command issuance.
                Responsibilities:
                - Implement periodic control loop with configurable T such that frequency equals sensor sampling rate.
                - On each iteration:
                  (1) Acquire sensor readings via SAL.
                  (2) Update grid map using Mapping module.
                  (3) Update Mission Control state machine.
                  (4) Compute/update current path as required by active state.
                  (5) Issue motor_set via Motion Controller and Motor Interface.
                - Provide measured cycle time or fixed period T to Pose Estimation and other time-based computations.
            </Purpose>
            <ConnectedComponents>
                <ConnectedComponent>
                    <Identifier>CMP--11</Identifier>
                    <Transmit>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SCHED_LoopTick</Name>
                            <Description>
                                See CMP--11. Triggers SAL sampling each cycle.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Transmit>
                    <Receive>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SAL_SamplingSchedule</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Sampling configuration from Reliability module; used to set loop frequency.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Receive>
                </ConnectedComponent>
                <ConnectedComponent>
                    <Identifier>CMP--12</Identifier>
                    <Transmit>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SCHED_MappingStepTrigger</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Triggers Mapping module processing sequence after SAL.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Transmit>
                    <Receive>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>MP_MappingDoneAck</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Optional ack from Mapping module; ensures mapping finishes before state machine update.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Receive>
                </ConnectedComponent>
                <ConnectedComponent>
                    <Identifier>CMP--1</Identifier>
                    <Transmit>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SCHED_MissionControlStepTrigger</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Ensures Mission Control is executed after mapping but before path planning and motor commands.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Transmit>
                    <Receive>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>MC_StepDoneAck</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Optional ack from Mission Control.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Receive>
                </ConnectedComponent>
                <ConnectedComponent>
                    <Identifier>CMP--3</Identifier>
                    <Transmit>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SCHED_PlannerTrigger</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Optional signal to Planner for path computations due in the current iteration; may be integrated directly in Mission Control or Motion Controller steps.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Transmit>
                    <Receive>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>PP_StepDoneAck</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Optional ack from Planner.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Receive>
                </ConnectedComponent>
                <ConnectedComponent>
                    <Identifier>CMP--4</Identifier>
                    <Transmit>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>SCHED_MotionControlTrigger</Name>
                            <Description>
                                At end of each loop iteration, Motion Controller is triggered to compute and send MC_MotorSet command.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Transmit>
                    <Receive>
                        <Signal>
                            <Name>MC_MotionDoneAck</Name>
                            <Description>
                                Optional ack from Motion Controller.
                            </Description>
                        </Signal>
                    </Receive>
                </ConnectedComponent>
            </ConnectedComponents>
            <Execution>
                - Control loop (repeats indefinitely until mission end):
                  while true:
                    - timestamp_start = current_time()
                    - Trigger SAL sampling (SCHED_LoopTick).
                    - Execute Mapping step (wall/cell updates, pose corrections).
                    - Execute Mission Control FSM step (CMP--1).
                    - Execute necessary planning steps (if MC requested).
                    - Execute Motion Control step including motor_set.
                    - Sleep until next cycle such that total period ≈ T; measure actual elapsed and provide to Pose Estimation.
                - Provide SCHED_LoopPeriod and SCHED_CurrentTime to modules needing timing.
            </Execution>
            <Timing>
                - T configured from Reliability module; sensor sampling rate = 1/T ∈ [10,50] Hz.
                - Timing jitter is bounded by tolerance specified elsewhere; scheduler will aim to minimize jitter.
            </Timing>
            <Invariants>
                - Sequence of operations per cycle is always SAL -&gt; Mapping -&gt; Mission Control -&gt; Planning -&gt; Motion.
                - Motor command issuance always occurs once per cycle at the end.
            </Invariants>
            <Failures>
                - Excessive jitter or missed cycles may degrade performance; must be monitored by platform but outside this design.
            </Failures>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--SCHED--1.1.1; LL--RELIAB--1.2.1; LL--INTERF--1.1.1; LL--INTERF--1.2.1; LL--MAP--1.1.2; LL--PLAN--1.1.1
            </DerivedFrom>
        </Component>
    </Components>

    <StateMachines version="1">
        <StateMachine>
            <ID>FSM--1</ID>
            <OfComponent>CMP--1</OfComponent>
            <States>
                <State>
                    <Name>IDLE</Name>
                    <StateAction>
                        - Monitor INIT_COMPLETED flag.
                        - Monitor SAL_SensorSnapshot.valid_flag values.
                        - Do not issue movement commands.
                    </StateAction>
                </State>
                <State>
                    <Name>EXPLORE</Name>
                    <StateAction>
                        - If no active exploration path, request frontier set and select target frontier.
                        - Request path to selected frontier and command Motion Controller to execute with exploration speed.
                        - Monitor exploration events (EXPLORATION_COMPLETED, EXPLORATION_TIMEOUT).
                        - Monitor path execution status; trigger replanning on BLOCKED/EMERGENCY_STOP or map updates.
                    </StateAction>
                </State>
                <State>
                    <Name>RETURN_TO_START</Name>
                    <StateAction>
                        - Invoke Return-to-start Service to compute path back to start cell.
                        - Command Motion Controller to execute return path.
                        - Monitor execution progress, replanning if invalidated.
                        - On reach start cell or planning failure, prepare for SECOND_RUN or COMPLETED.
                    </StateAction>
                </State>
                <State>
                    <Name>SECOND_RUN</Name>
                    <StateAction>
                        - Request/confirm goal region selection.
                        - Configure planner for fastest path.
                        - Command Motion Controller to execute fastest path with higher speed profile.
                        - Monitor success/failure conditions (arrival at goal region, collisions).
                    </StateAction>
                </State>
                <State>
                    <Name>COMPLETED</Name>
                    <StateAction>
                        - Cease issuing new motion commands.
                        - Maintain final second-run status for external reporting.
                    </StateAction>
                </State>
            </States>
            <Transitions>
                <Transition>
                    <From>IDLE</From>
                    <To>EXPLORE</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        INIT_COMPLETED flag set by Initialization module AND at least one valid set of ultrasonic and infrared sensor measurements available from SAL in the current or a previous control loop iteration.
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - Mission has not yet started (first transition from IDLE).
                        - No fault condition inhibiting exploration is active.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Set exploration start timestamp by sending MC_ExplorationStartNotification to Exploration-Status module.
                        - Initialize internal exploration counters and flags.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
                <Transition>
                    <From>EXPLORE</From>
                    <To>RETURN_TO_START</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        EXPLORATION_COMPLETED event dequeued from system event queue OR EXPLORATION_TIMEOUT event dequeued; whichever occurs first.
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - Event has not already been consumed for this mission.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Send MC_ExplorationStopNotification to Exploration-Status module.
                        - Invoke Return-to-start Service with trigger_source according to event type.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
                <Transition>
                    <From>RETURN_TO_START</From>
                    <To>SECOND_RUN</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        - Return path execution completed successfully (Motion Controller reports execution_state == COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell).
                        - Exploration previously declared complete (EXPLORATION_COMPLETED event had occurred, not timeout-only).
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - No planning failure occurred for return path.
                        - Exploration status indicates map completeness.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Initiate Second-run planning via MC_SecondRunInvoke.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
                <Transition>
                    <From>RETURN_TO_START</From>
                    <To>COMPLETED</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        - Return path planning failure (RS_ReturnPathStatus PATH_PLANNING_FAILED), OR
                        - Execution cannot reach start cell due to repeated BLOCKED/EMERGENCY_STOP and no alternative paths.
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - Replanning attempts exhausted or explicitly limited by configuration.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Set mission final status to failure.
                        - Issue STOP command to Motion Controller to ensure motors are halted.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
                <Transition>
                    <From>SECOND_RUN</From>
                    <To>COMPLETED</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        - Second-run execution result becomes available from Second-run Planning module indicating success or failure.
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - SECOND_RUN path planning has been attempted.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Store final second-run status (success or failure).
                        - If needed, issue STOP to Motion Controller.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
                <Transition>
                    <From>EXPLORE</From>
                    <To>COMPLETED</To>
                    <Trigger>
                        Optional direct mission abort if unrecoverable system fault occurs during exploration (e.g. hardware failure).
                    </Trigger>
                    <Guard>
                        - System fault flag set.
                    </Guard>
                    <TransitionAction>
                        - Stop all motion; set mission status to failure.
                    </TransitionAction>
                </Transition>
            </Transitions>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--MAP--1.1.1; LL--MAP--1.1.2; LL--MAP--1.1.3; LL--MAP--1.5.1; LL--RUN--1.1.1; LL--RUN--1.2.1;
                LL--RUN--1.2.4; LL--RUN--1.2.5; LL--EVENT--1.1.1; LL--INIT--1.1.1; LL--SCHED--1.1.1
            </DerivedFrom>
        </StateMachine>
    </StateMachines>

    <AdditionalData version="1">
        <Data>
            <ID>DAT--1</ID>
            <Content>
                Enumeration Definitions

                CellState (for grid cells):
                - UNKNOWN: cell not yet explored; default after initialization.
                - FREE: robot has successfully traversed into cell without collision and sensor data are consistent; used as traversable nodes in path planner.
                - BLOCKED: inferred obstacle cell not to be entered; path planner and motion controller treat as non-traversable.

                WallState (for inter-cell walls):
                - UNKNOWN: wall presence/absence not yet observed.
                - PRESENT: wall detected between adjacent cells; movement across this boundary must not be commanded.
                - ABSENT: no wall between cells; movement allowed for FREE cells.

                MissionState (for Mission Control FSM):
                - IDLE
                - EXPLORE
                - RETURN_TO_START
                - SECOND_RUN
                - COMPLETED

                PathRequestType:
                - EXPLORATION_TO_FRONTIER
                - RETURN_TO_START
                - SECOND_RUN_TO_GOAL

                PlannerStatus:
                - SUCCESS
                - FAILURE_NO_PATH

                ExecutionState (for path execution status):
                - IDLE
                - EXECUTING
                - BLOCKED
                - COMPLETED
                - EMERGENCY_STOP

                SecondRunResult:
                - SECOND_RUN_SUCCESS
                - SECOND_RUN_FAILURE
            </Content>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--MAP--1.4.1; LL--MAP--1.4.2; LL--MAP--1.1.1; LL--PLAN--1.1.1; LL--PLAN--1.1.5;
                LL--RUN--1.2.4; LL--RUN--1.2.5
            </DerivedFrom>
        </Data>
        <Data>
            <ID>DAT--2</ID>
            <Content>
                Collision and Clearance Geometry

                Environment parameters:
                - cell_size_cm ≈ 17.2 cm (LL--ENV--1.2.1).
                - wall_thickness_cm ≈ 1.6 cm (LL--ENV--1.3.1).
                - robot_radius_cm = 5.5 cm (LL--HARDWARE--1.1.1).
                - min_clearance_margin_cm = M &gt; 0 cm (configurable, from Reliability module, LL--RELIAB--1.1.1).

                For a robot modeled as a circle of radius R moving along a corridor between walls:
                - Minimum distance from robot center to any wall must always be ≥ (R + M).
                - For grid-map-based collision checks:
                    * Represent walls as line segments at cell boundaries.
                    * When robot is at cell center, distance to front wall for a corridor with single cell spacing:
                        d_nominal ≈ (cell_size_cm / 2) - (wall_thickness_cm/2) - robot_radius_cm.
                    * For front wall detection using ultrasonic distance d:
                        - Consider interval [d-12,d+12].
                        - Compare to expected interval [d_nominal - epsilon, d_nominal + epsilon] where epsilon accounts for pose uncertainty.
                        - If intersection non-empty, classify wall as PRESENT.

                Clearance against path:
                - For each candidate motion primitive, approximate swept path of robot circle.
                - Ensure distance from path centerline to any PRESENT wall's geometric line, minus robot_radius, is ≥ M.
                - If not, motion primitive is disallowed for planning and execution.
            </Content>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--HARDWARE--1.1.1; LL--ENV--1.2.1; LL--ENV--1.3.1; LL--MAP--1.2.1; LL--MAP--1.2.4;
                LL--RELIAB--1.1.1; LL--INTERF--2.3.1
            </DerivedFrom>
        </Data>
        <Data>
            <ID>DAT--3</ID>
            <Content>
                Time-Aware Planning Calculations

                Global mapping time limit:
                - Max exploration time T_max = 5 minutes = 300000 ms (LL--MAP--1.5.1).

                Nominal cell traversal duration parameter:
                - Parameter t_cell_ms: nominal time to traverse one cell at exploration speed (LL--MAP--1.5.3).
                - Recommended configuration range based on empirical tests; accessible via Exploration Status module.

                Remaining time estimation:
                - Let t_elapsed_ms be elapsed time since exploration start.
                - Remaining time: t_rem_ms = max(0, T_max - t_elapsed_ms).
                - For a prospective frontier target with path cost C (in edge units) and cost scaling factor k(ms/unit):
                    * Estimated travel time: t_travel_ms = k * C.
                    * Estimated mapping time at target (local exploration) ≈ t_cell_ms.
                    * Combined estimate: t_estimate_ms = t_travel_ms + t_cell_ms.

                Frontier feasibility condition:
                - A frontier target is feasible if t_estimate_ms ≤ t_rem_ms.
                - Frontier selection coarse filtering: discard all targets with t_estimate_ms &gt; t_rem_ms before heuristic evaluation.

                Planner cost profile mapping:
                - For exploration:
                    * Use cost_straight = 1 unit, cost_turn ≥ 1 (e.g. 1.2) and map k_explore = t_cell_ms (per cell) for time approximation.
                - For second run (fastest path):
                    * Choose cost_straight tuned so that path minimizing (number_of_cells * 1 + number_of_turns * turn_penalty) approximates shortest travel time.
                    * Speed profile for second run uses higher translational velocity while ensuring safe stopping per Reliability module.

            </Content>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--MAP--1.5.1; LL--MAP--1.5.2; LL--MAP--1.5.3; LL--PLAN--1.1.2
            </DerivedFrom>
        </Data>
        <Data>
            <ID>DAT--4</ID>
            <Content>
                Sensor Consistency and Hysteresis Configuration

                Consistency parameter N:
                - N is an integer ≥ 2 with default value 3 (LL--RELIAB--1.2.2).
                - Recommended range: 2 ≤ N ≤ 10.
                - When new sensor readings contradict current map classification (e.g., wall indicated where map says ABSENT/FREE), require at least N consecutive contradictory readings before changing classification.

                Wall proximity hysteresis:
                - For ultrasonic readings, define two thresholds:
                  * d_wall_detect_cm: if filtered distance &lt;= d_wall_detect_cm, treat as wall present candidate.
                  * d_free_detect_cm: if filtered distance &gt;= d_free_detect_cm, treat as wall absent candidate.
                  * d_free_detect_cm &gt; d_wall_detect_cm to provide hysteresis.
                - State machine for front wall classification per cell face:
                  * UNKNOWN:
                      - If stable wall indications (duration or consecutive count) reached, change to PRESENT.
                      - If stable free indications, change to ABSENT.
                  * PRESENT:
                      - Changes only allowed if allowed by Static Map Assumption (forbid PRESENT→ABSENT); in this design, no change is permitted.
                  * ABSENT:
                      - Similarly, no change to PRESENT unless overriding safety design; main spec forbids this.

                IR hysteresis:
                - Use K (K≥1, often equal to N) consecutive samples with same obstacle flag to change IR state; prevents flicker due to noise.

            </Content>
            <DerivedFrom>
                LL--MAP--1.2.3; LL--RELIAB--1.2.1; LL--RELIAB--1.2.2
            </DerivedFrom>
        </Data>
    </AdditionalData>
</Design>
[2026-05-20--17:15:12]User: Your Design will be verified by another engineer. All Mistakes will be given to you as findings.
You will have to incorporate them into your Design, and give a document as answer.
This process is defined in this document:

Software Findings Policy (SFP)

When a Verifier notices an Error or Inconsistency in any Document a Finding is created, which details the Error, Its location and a possible solution.
The creator of the Original Document has to process each Finding and either implement the solution, or justify why the problem does not need to be fixed.

Findings Document Structure
1. Findings are to be structured using XML files.
2. A Findings Document always contain findings of only one document
3. All documents must start with the <Findings> tag.
4. The <Findings> tag must have three attributes:
   a. “version”: the findings documents version
   b. “source”: specifies the type of document the findings reference
   c. “source_version”: specifies the version of the source document

Findings Structure
6.  Below the <Findings> tag, every finding must be stored inside its own <Finding> tag.
    a. each finding must have the attribute "id"

7. Each Finding must have the following children
    a. <ItemID> The ID of the Item the Finding references
    b. <Description> Description of the Finding
    c. <Solution> A Suggestion as how to fix the Problem
    d. <Severity> Severity how the finding

8. Findings can have the following children, in certain circumstances
    e <RollbackPhase> to which phase the development needs to be rolled back to fix the findings

Finding Template

<Findings version="{version}" source= "{source}" source_version = "{source_version}"  >
    <Finding ID = "{finding id}">
        <ItemID> {RequirementID} </ItemID>
        <Severity> {Severity} </Severity>
        <Description> {Description} </Description>
        <Solution> {Solution} </Solution>
        <RollbackPhase> {Optional: Rollback Phase}</RollbackPhase>
    </Finding>
</Findings>

Identification
  The content of the findings <ID> tag must conform to the pattern:
  "{source_type}--{source_version}--{counter}"
  "source_type": The type of the source document
  "source_version": The version of the source document
  "counter": The number of the finding of the document, starting with 1

Severity
    Severity can have 3 Grades
    a. "Minor": Only affects one item, minor changes needed in the current phase
    b. "Major": Affects multiple items, major changes needed in the current phase
    c. "Catastrophic": Affects multiple items, it is necessary to change items in prior phases

    Whenever a catastrophic finding is detected, only catastrophic findings are to be documented.
    Catastrophic findings need to have the Rollback Phase child, indicating to which phase the process needs to be rolled back to fix the problem.
    It is advised to only roll back to the previous phase, but it is possible to rollback multiple phases
    The phases are as follows:
    a. "High Level Requirements"
    b. "Low Level Requirements"
    c. "Design"
    d. "Implementation"



Answer Document Structure
1. Answers are to be structured using XML files.
2. A Answer Document contains only the answer to one Findings document
3. All documents must start with the <Answer> tag.
4. The <Findings> tag must have one attributes:
   b. “findings_version”: specifies the version of the findings document, the answer is to
   c. “findings_type”: specifies the type of document the finding document references

Findings Structure
5. Below the <Findings> tag, every answer must be stored inside its own <Justification> or <Implementation> tag.

Justification Structure
6. Each Justification must have the following children
    a. <FindingID> The ID of the Finding the Answer references
    b. <Explanation> Explanation why the Finding does not need to be fixed

Implementation Structure
7. Each Implementation must have the following children
    a. <FindingID> The ID of the Finding the Answer references
    b. <Explanation> Explanation of how the Finding was Fixed

<Answer findings_version= "{findings_version}" findings_type "{findings_type}">
    <Justification>
        <FindingID> {Finding ID} </FindingID>
        <Explanation> {Explanation} </Explanation>
    </Justification>

    <Implementation>
        <FindingID> {Finding ID} </FindingID>
        <Solution> {Solution} </Solution>
    </Implementation>
</Answer>

Justification
    A Justification is needed whenever a Finding is not Accepted, it needs to explain why the Finding is not correct
    When the Finding Author does not agree with the Justification, another Finding, referencing the same Item as the original Finding needs to be created, arguing against the Justification

 


