    <Implementation>
        <FindingID>Design--1--1</FindingID>
        <Explanation>
            The status signal transmitted by the Motion Controller component has been renamed to clearly indicate CMP--8 as the sender and to remove ambiguity with Mission Control initiated signals.

            Changes:
            - In CMP--8 (Motion Control and Collision Avoidance), the transmitted signal previously named &quot;MC_PathExecutionStatus&quot; is now named &quot;MCtrl_PathExecutionStatus&quot;, with an updated description explicitly stating it is initiated by Motion Controller.
            - In CMP--1 (Mission Control State Machine), the corresponding Receive signal name has been updated from &quot;MC_PathExecutionStatus&quot; to &quot;MCtrl_PathExecutionStatus&quot; with matching semantics.
            - FSM--1 textual references inside Mission Control Execution logic that depended on the path execution status now refer to &quot;MCtrl_PathExecutionStatus&quot; for clarity.

            This ensures the naming convention &quot;MCtrl_...&quot; identifies Motion Controller-originated signals and removes the directional ambiguity noted in the finding.
        </Explanation>
    </Implementation>

    <Implementation>
        <FindingID>Design--1--2</FindingID>
        <Explanation>
            The optional feedback signal from Motion Controller to the Path Planner was removed to keep interfaces minimal and symmetric, as it was not required by the LLRs and not used by CMP--4.

            Changes:
            - In CMP--8 (Motion Control and Collision Avoidance), the ConnectedComponent entry that referenced CMP--4 (Path Planner) and the transmit signal &quot;MC_CurrentPathFeedback&quot; have been removed entirely. CPM--8 no longer lists CMP--4 as a connected component.
            - CMP--4 (Path Planner) already did not refer to any such feedback signal or a connection to CMP--8; no changes were necessary there.

            As a result, there is now no asymmetrical interface definition: Motion Controller does not claim a dependency on the planner beyond what is mediated by Mission Control, consistent with the topology described in CMP--1. This follows option (2) of the proposed solution.
        </Explanation>
    </Implementation>

    <Implementation>
        <FindingID>Design--1--3</FindingID>
        <Explanation>
            The wording in the Mission Control Execution description has been aligned with the ExecutionState enumeration defined in DAT--1 to avoid ambiguity.

            Changes:
            - In CMP--1 Execution, RETURN_TO_START handling previously said: &quot;Monitor MC_PathExecutionStatus; when EXECUTION COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell...&quot;.
            - This has been changed to: &quot;Monitor MCtrl_PathExecutionStatus each cycle. When execution_state == COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell...&quot;.

            The ExecutionState enumeration in DAT--1 now uses:
            - EXEC_STATE_IDLE
            - EXEC_STATE_EXECUTING
            - EXEC_STATE_BLOCKED
            - EXEC_STATE_COMPLETED
            - EXEC_STATE_EMERGENCY_STOP

            and the narrative text references the semantic value COMPLETED, matching the enumeration semantics and resolving the inconsistency.
        </Explanation>
    </Implementation>

    <Implementation>
